Update `apps/client/src/layers/features/extensions/ui/ManifestSecretsPanel.tsx` to (a) use the secret's `placeholder` field instead of the key name, and (b) organize secrets by `group` using `CollapsibleFieldCard` for named groups.

This task delivers visible UI improvements (placeholder hints and grouped secrets) before the full settings panel work in Phase 3.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Update the PasswordInput placeholder

In the `SecretRow` component (line 172), the placeholder currently uses `secret.key.replace(/_/g, '_')` which is effectively just the key name. Replace with:

```typescript
placeholder={secret.placeholder ?? secret.key}
```

This uses the manifest-declared placeholder if available, falling back to the key name for backward compatibility.

### 2. Add grouping logic to ManifestSecretsPanel

Replace the flat list rendering in the `ManifestSecretsPanel` component (lines 67-81) with a grouped layout:

```typescript
import {
  FieldCard,
  FieldCardContent,
  CollapsibleFieldCard,
  SettingRow,
  PasswordInput,
  Badge,
  Button,
} from '@/layers/shared/ui';
```

Add a grouping helper function above the component:

```typescript
/** Group secrets by their `group` field. Ungrouped items have key `undefined`. */
function groupSecrets(
  secrets: SecretDeclaration[],
  statuses: Map<string, boolean>
): Map<string | undefined, Array<{ secret: SecretDeclaration; isSet: boolean }>> {
  const grouped = new Map<string | undefined, Array<{ secret: SecretDeclaration; isSet: boolean }>>();
  for (const secret of secrets) {
    const group = secret.group;
    if (!grouped.has(group)) grouped.set(group, []);
    grouped.get(group)!.push({
      secret,
      isSet: statuses.get(secret.key) ?? false,
    });
  }
  return grouped;
}
```

Update the render body of `ManifestSecretsPanel`:

```typescript
const grouped = groupSecrets(secrets, statuses);
const ungrouped = grouped.get(undefined);
const namedGroups = [...grouped.entries()].filter(([key]) => key !== undefined) as Array<
  [string, Array<{ secret: SecretDeclaration; isSet: boolean }>]
>;

return (
  <>
    {/* Ungrouped secrets render in a flat FieldCard */}
    {ungrouped && ungrouped.length > 0 && (
      <FieldCard>
        <FieldCardContent>
          {ungrouped.map(({ secret, isSet }) => (
            <SecretRow
              key={secret.key}
              extensionId={extensionId}
              secret={secret}
              isSet={isSet}
              onChanged={fetchStatuses}
            />
          ))}
        </FieldCardContent>
      </FieldCard>
    )}

    {/* Named groups render as CollapsibleFieldCards */}
    {namedGroups.map(([groupName, items]) => (
      <CollapsibleFieldCard key={groupName} title={groupName} defaultOpen>
        {items.map(({ secret, isSet }) => (
          <SecretRow
            key={secret.key}
            extensionId={extensionId}
            secret={secret}
            isSet={isSet}
            onChanged={fetchStatuses}
          />
        ))}
      </CollapsibleFieldCard>
    ))}
  </>
);
```

Note: Check the `CollapsibleFieldCard` component API. It likely accepts `title` and `defaultOpen` props and renders children inside. Verify by reading `apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/field-card.tsx` if needed.

### 3. Update the loading state

Keep the existing loading state skeleton but use the same wrapping (a single `FieldCard`).

## Acceptance Criteria

- When a secret has `placeholder: 'lin_api_xxxx'`, the PasswordInput shows `lin_api_xxxx` as placeholder text
- When a secret has no `placeholder`, the PasswordInput shows the key name (backward compatible)
- Secrets with no `group` render in a flat `FieldCard` at the top
- Secrets with `group: 'GitHub'` render inside a `CollapsibleFieldCard` titled "GitHub"
- Multiple groups render as separate collapsible sections
- Existing functionality (save, clear, isSet badge) is preserved
- All existing tests continue to pass

Add the `SettingsStore` interface to `packages/extension-api/src/server-extension-api.ts` and extend the `DataProviderContext` interface with a `settings` field.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add SettingsStore interface

Add the following interface after the existing `SecretStore` interface (after line 20):

```typescript
/** Read/write access to non-secret extension configuration (plaintext JSON). */
export interface SettingsStore {
  /** Get a setting value by key. Returns null if not set. */
  get<T extends string | number | boolean = string | number | boolean>(
    key: string
  ): Promise<T | null>;
  /** Set a setting value. Writes through to disk immediately. */
  set(key: string, value: string | number | boolean): Promise<void>;
  /** Delete a setting value. Writes through to disk immediately. */
  delete(key: string): Promise<void>;
  /** Get all stored settings as a key-value record. */
  getAll(): Promise<Record<string, string | number | boolean>>;
}
```

### 2. Extend DataProviderContext

Add `settings` to the `DataProviderContext` interface (currently lines 23-39). Add it after the `secrets` field:

```typescript
export interface DataProviderContext {
  /** Encrypted per-extension secret store. */
  readonly secrets: SecretStore;
  /** Non-secret extension configuration store (plaintext JSON). */
  readonly settings: SettingsStore;
  /** Scoped persistent storage for extension data. */
  readonly storage: {
    loadData<T = unknown>(): Promise<T | null>;
    saveData<T = unknown>(data: T): Promise<void>;
  };
  schedule(intervalSeconds: number, fn: () => Promise<void>): () => void;
  emit(event: string, data: unknown): void;
  readonly extensionId: string;
  readonly extensionDir: string;
}
```

### 3. Update barrel exports

Update `packages/extension-api/src/index.ts` to add `SettingsStore` to the server-extension-api.js exports:

```typescript
export type {
  SecretStore,
  SettingsStore,
  DataProviderContext,
  ServerExtensionRegister,
} from './server-extension-api.js';
```

## Impact

Adding `settings` to `DataProviderContext` will cause a TypeScript error in `apps/server/src/services/extensions/extension-server-api-factory.ts` because the factory does not yet provide a `settings` value. This is resolved in task 2.3. The tasks should be implemented sequentially within Phase 2.

## Acceptance Criteria

- `SettingsStore` interface is exported from `@dorkos/extension-api/server`
- `SettingsStore` interface is exported from `@dorkos/extension-api` (via barrel)
- `DataProviderContext` includes `readonly settings: SettingsStore`
- `import type { SettingsStore } from '@dorkos/extension-api'` resolves correctly
- The generic `get<T>` method constrains T to `string | number | boolean`

Create a new file `packages/shared/src/extension-settings.ts` implementing the `SettingsStore` interface with plaintext JSON file storage. Follow the `ExtensionSecretStore` pattern from `packages/shared/src/extension-secrets.ts` but without encryption.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Create the file

Create `packages/shared/src/extension-settings.ts`:

```typescript
/**
 * Plaintext per-extension settings store.
 *
 * Settings are stored in `{dorkHome}/extension-settings/{extensionId}.json`.
 * Unlike secrets, settings are not encrypted — they hold non-sensitive
 * configuration values (refresh intervals, display toggles, filter selections).
 *
 * @module shared/extension-settings
 */
import { readFile, writeFile, mkdir, rename } from 'node:fs/promises';
import { join, dirname } from 'node:path';
import type { SettingsStore } from '@dorkos/extension-api/server';

/**
 * Plaintext per-extension settings store using JSON files.
 *
 * Each extension gets its own JSON file under `{dorkHome}/extension-settings/`.
 * Writes use the atomic temp-file-then-rename pattern for safety.
 */
export class ExtensionSettingsStore implements SettingsStore {
  private readonly filePath: string;

  constructor(dorkHome: string, extensionId: string) {
    const dir = join(dorkHome, 'extension-settings');
    this.filePath = join(dir, `${extensionId}.json`);
  }

  /** Get a setting value by key. Returns null if not set. */
  async get<T extends string | number | boolean = string | number | boolean>(
    key: string
  ): Promise<T | null> {
    const data = await this.loadAll();
    return (data[key] as T) ?? null;
  }

  /** Set a setting value. Writes through to disk immediately. */
  async set(key: string, value: string | number | boolean): Promise<void> {
    const data = await this.loadAll();
    data[key] = value;
    await this.saveAll(data);
  }

  /** Delete a setting value. Writes through to disk immediately. */
  async delete(key: string): Promise<void> {
    const data = await this.loadAll();
    delete data[key];
    await this.saveAll(data);
  }

  /** Get all stored settings as a key-value record. */
  async getAll(): Promise<Record<string, string | number | boolean>> {
    return this.loadAll();
  }

  private async loadAll(): Promise<Record<string, string | number | boolean>> {
    try {
      const raw = await readFile(this.filePath, 'utf-8');
      return JSON.parse(raw) as Record<string, string | number | boolean>;
    } catch {
      return {};
    }
  }

  private async saveAll(data: Record<string, string | number | boolean>): Promise<void> {
    const dir = dirname(this.filePath);
    await mkdir(dir, { recursive: true });
    const tmp = this.filePath + '.tmp';
    await writeFile(tmp, JSON.stringify(data, null, 2), 'utf-8');
    await rename(tmp, this.filePath);
  }
}
```

Key differences from `ExtensionSecretStore`:
- No encryption/decryption
- No host key management
- No in-memory cache (file is tiny, reads are infrequent)
- Stores in `extension-settings/` (not `extension-secrets/`)
- Values are `string | number | boolean` (not just `string`)

### 2. Add subpath export to packages/shared/package.json

Follow the existing pattern for `extension-secrets`. Add to the `exports` field in `packages/shared/package.json`:

```json
"./extension-settings": {
  "types": "./src/extension-settings.ts",
  "default": "./dist/extension-settings.js"
}
```

Place it near the existing `./extension-secrets` entry.

## Acceptance Criteria

- `ExtensionSettingsStore` implements `SettingsStore` interface
- `get()` returns `null` for missing keys
- `set()` stores and persists string, number, and boolean values
- `delete()` removes a key and persists the change
- `getAll()` returns all stored key-value pairs
- Different extension IDs use isolated JSON files
- Atomic writes use temp-file-then-rename
- Constructor takes `dorkHome` as required first parameter (no fallback chain)
- `@dorkos/shared/extension-settings` subpath export resolves correctly

Add three new API endpoints to `apps/server/src/routes/extensions.ts` for settings management: GET (list with defaults), PUT (store value), DELETE (reset to default).

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add imports

Add the `ExtensionSettingsStore` import:

```typescript
import { ExtensionSettingsStore } from '@dorkos/shared/extension-settings';
```

And the validation schema for the PUT body:

```typescript
const SetSettingBodySchema = z.object({
  value: z.union([z.string(), z.number(), z.boolean()]),
});
```

### 2. GET /api/extensions/:id/settings

Add after the existing DELETE secrets endpoint (after line 342). This endpoint returns all declared settings with their current values merged with defaults:

```typescript
// GET /api/extensions/:id/settings -- List declared settings with current values
router.get('/:id/settings', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { id } = req.params;
    if (!SAFE_EXT_ID.test(id)) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid extension ID' });

    const record = extensionManager.get(id);
    if (!record) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: `Extension '${id}' not found` });
    }

    const declared = record.manifest.serverCapabilities?.settings ?? [];
    const store = new ExtensionSettingsStore(dorkHome, id);
    const stored = await store.getAll();

    const result = declared.map((s) => {
      const hasStored = s.key in stored;
      return {
        key: s.key,
        type: s.type,
        label: s.label,
        description: s.description,
        placeholder: s.placeholder,
        group: s.group,
        value: hasStored ? stored[s.key] : (s.default ?? null),
        isDefault: !hasStored,
        ...(s.options && { options: s.options }),
        ...(s.min !== undefined && { min: s.min }),
        ...(s.max !== undefined && { max: s.max }),
      };
    });

    res.json(result);
  } catch (err) {
    logger.error(`[Extensions] Failed to list settings for ${req.params.id}`, err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Failed to list settings' });
  }
});
```

### 3. PUT /api/extensions/:id/settings/:key

Store a setting value, validating the key is declared in the manifest:

```typescript
// PUT /api/extensions/:id/settings/:key -- Store a setting value
router.put('/:id/settings/:key', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { id, key } = req.params;
    if (!SAFE_EXT_ID.test(id)) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid extension ID' });

    const parsed = SetSettingBodySchema.safeParse(req.body);
    if (!parsed.success) {
      return res
        .status(400)
        .json({ error: 'Validation failed', details: parsed.error.flatten() });
    }

    const record = extensionManager.get(id);
    if (!record) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: `Extension '${id}' not found` });
    }

    // Validate key is declared in manifest
    const declared = record.manifest.serverCapabilities?.settings ?? [];
    if (!declared.some((s) => s.key === key)) {
      return res
        .status(400)
        .json({ error: `Setting '${key}' not declared in extension manifest` });
    }

    const store = new ExtensionSettingsStore(dorkHome, id);
    await store.set(key, parsed.data.value);
    res.json({ ok: true });
  } catch (err) {
    logger.error(`[Extensions] Failed to set setting for ${req.params.id}`, err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Failed to set setting' });
  }
});
```

### 4. DELETE /api/extensions/:id/settings/:key

Reset a setting to its default by removing the stored override:

```typescript
// DELETE /api/extensions/:id/settings/:key -- Reset setting to default
router.delete('/:id/settings/:key', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { id, key } = req.params;
    if (!SAFE_EXT_ID.test(id)) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid extension ID' });

    const record = extensionManager.get(id);
    if (!record) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: `Extension '${id}' not found` });
    }

